story: Hey! We are the Miss kick ambassadors! A group of girls from different places in the world with the ambition to make it as a professional footballer ! Miss kick was founded by Grace Vella, someone who is very passionate about the game! Grace wants to give young girls the best oppourtunity that she can! Miss kick is the Uk world leading Female Football Brand. We have set up this just giving page with the aim of raising money for charities;that are close to our heart. Unfortunately some of us have lost loved ones to these awful illnesses and we want to help stop others from experiencing the loss of someone they love! These charities are: Dementia Support, Macmillian Cancer Support and Darby Rimmer MND Foundation! Our aim as a team is to reach 150km in March. We will aim to do this by staying active whether this is running,skipping,hopping,jumping,crawling or cycling etc. If we reach this target then we are hoping to increase it and set another target! Any donations would be very much appreciated!

story:
I started my small business after loosing my dad to cancer and it helped me through the grieving and trauma by learning to make memory bears to bring small comfort to other families after the loss of loved ones.

In these extraordinary times, Macmillan’s priority is the health and well-being of people with cancer.

Right now, MacMillan nurses, doctors and other health professionals up and down the country are continuing to support people living with cancer whilst doing all they can to help alleviate the immense strain put on the NHS by corona virus. Many Macmillan services are having to take difficult decisions to change the way they operate or even close .

story:
The Big Boat Pull is a two year charity fund-raising event with the aim of raising £10,000 for Macmillan cancer support.

During the summer of 2021, I aim to pull my narrowboat the full 16 mile length of the Gloucester & Sharpness canal.  With a 10 tonne boat at the age 74 isn't an easy task...  During the summer of 2022 will be the second and much bigger event.  Along with a team of volunteers, we will pull the boat all the way from Gloucester to Liverpool, a distance of around 220 miles.

Throughout the 2 years, I will also be painting various items in the
traditional canal-art style which will be offered for sale with a
requested minimum donation.

charity.name: Macmillan Cancer Support
story:
Cancer is something that unfortunately affects us all at some point in our lives, whether it be losing a family member, a friend or watching somebody take on the brave battle against the disease. Sadly not everyone wins the battle and the news is devastating to everyone involved. When somebody is diagnosed with terminal cancer, Macmillan nurses are there to provide palliative care towards the end of life, as well as ensuring the patient remains comfortable, well looked after and to provide emotional support to families.

Knowing that somebody is at the end of their life is a heartbreaking and unimaginable situation to be in, however knowing that McMillan are there to support for the final journey can be a real comfort in such a difficult time. 

Macmillan relies on donations, funding and sponsorship to be able to continue the invaluable service they offer. 

With this is mind, I have decided I want to use the bit of spare time I have whilst we are in lockdown to raise money for a cause close to my heart. In March, I have set myself a target of completing over 100 miles of running. To some this may not sound much, to others this may sound a lot.. to me, this is a huge challenge! I am by no means an athlete nor am I a runner, however knowing I’m raising money whilst doing so will give me a huge kick up the bum! 

I will be linking my Strava activity to this page so you can see my progress and I will also be posting weekly updates. 

All money raised on this page will be sent directly to Macmillan. No matter how small; every donation will count and means a lot to me, as it will to the family who it will go forward to help. 

Please support me on my challenge, and continue to support the amazing things that Macmillan do. 

Annabelle x

story:
Having been approached by dear friends to take on a Macmillan Mighty Hike it did initially seem a totally different experience for me having run the two marathons and several half marathons in the past.  I then remembered the reason behind taking on any form of challenge and decided what better way to raise funds for an amazing charity than to walk 26.2 miles with dear friends and my cousin.  I'm looking forward to a challenge for my 40th birthday in July also!  

We have lost dear friends and family from this awful disease and every day hear of those who are struggling and battling through every day so simply want to help in any way I can towards this amazing charity.  EVERY little helps and I am truly grateful for all of you who donate, read my story and for all the encouragement along the way.

story:
In December 2019 my husband, Mike, was diagnosed with prostate cancer and so our world cam crashing down. Each one of us dealt with the news in our own way. Good or bad makes no difference. Lots of emotions, fear, anger, sadness all at once. Understanding treatments and impact and how to support Mike to make a decision what's best for him. Then frustration and worry as COVID hits the world and treatment is delayed. I begun to unravel, putting on a brave face for Mike and our sons, Max and Alex. Must stay strong, not give up, breaking is not an option. I knew I needed to speak to someone and cry, scream, talk, vent. I reached out to Macmillan, who put me in contact with the most amazing counsellor. I am so grateful for her support. She listened and asked questions, sometimes hard ones and helped me deal with the emotional roller coaster. She helped me understand that it is ok to not be ok, which was a profound discovery for me. Because of lockdown our sessions were remote, but still took place and I cannot tell you how lucky I felt to be able to have this support.

Thankfully, Mike's treatment begun in September 2020 and he is on way to recovery. Our days are definitely brighter. He has been so brave and strong, and I and our boys are so proud of him.

Cancer is frightening and affects everyone in family. It is so important to have someone to reach out to.

So here we are , me Max and Alex taking on the Thames Path Mighty Hike challenge, to raise some funds for Macmillan, so that their great work may continue. 

We are joining others in a 26 miles hike along the River Thames on July 17th. It will definitely be a challenged for me, personally, but I am buzzing with excitement.


Please support us so we can help Macmillan

 
Thank you
Wojtkiewicz family

charity.name: British Heart Foundation
story:
Please help me raise £250 for the British Heart Foundation so we can also help others. I know I'm always up to something, but this one will be a real challenge for me as I'm essentially rubbish at swimming, and I'm far more inclined to relax in warm waters with a beer in my hand than the cold British waters!  I will be attempting to swim 1.4 miles of open water sea swimming from Bournemouth pier to Boscombe Pier. With waves, currents and salt water this is going to be really hard work, and definitely outside of my comfort zone.  This is going to be even harder to train for due to lockdown restrictions closing my local pool, and the sea being outside my local vicinity to go and practise so I now have added incentive to hope that the lockdown restrictions all ease as anticipated!! 

A little under two years ago my mum was diagnosed with a degenerative aortic heart valve, which proceeded to degenerate at an alarming rate. From being active, independent and enjoying her daily walks, she rapidly lost confidence and the ability to manage even 200 metres without becoming breathless. Eventually she was admitted to hospital as an emergency case with less than 27% function of her heart, and the most she could do was walk 3 metres to an en suite bathroom and back.  One successful heart valve replacement and two months later (Feb 2021) she is now comfortably walking over a mile, is confident to drive and is rapidly regaining a quality of life which will hopefully last for the next 15 years.  The research and development of heart surgery has essentially given my mum her life back. She is one of the lucky ones.  

I'm raising money for the British Heart Foundation and I'd be so grateful for your support. The BHF has helped halve the number of people dying from heart and circulatory disease in the UK but sadly every day hundreds of people lose their lives, sadly including past friends of mine.  Every pound helps so please give what you can to help me hit my target. Thanks in advance!

charity.name: British Heart Foundation
story:
This is a very personal appeal, and I thank you for taking the time to read this...

Last year my dad suffered a heart attack, and it's only because of the incredible response and care from his neighbours, ambulance crew, paramedics, surgeons, cardiologists and nurses, that I'm lucky to still have him today.

Research carried out by the British Heart Foundation has helped towards creating the vast network of life savers we have today; from simply knowing what the symptoms of a heart attack are, performing CPR, how to use a defibrillator, emergency procedures, preventative surgeries and rehabilitation. All of these wouldn't be known without research that is carried out by organisations such as BHF.

The BHF has helped halve the number of people dying from heart and circulatory disease in the UK but sadly every day hundreds of people still lose their lives. It's only thanks to support from people like us that the BHF can create new treatments and discover new cures. £24 could pay for two hours of research by an early career scientist, research that could be groundbreaking, but every pound helps so please give what you can to help.

Any donation would be hugely appreciated, as I hope that this funding will go towards saving more lives in the future.

All my thanks <3

charity.name: British Heart Foundation
story:
I've decided to give up sweets and all things chocolate for 31 days to raise money for British Heart Foundation.  It is a charity close to my heart because my amazing grandad was taken from us at the age of 62 with a heart attack.  

Anyone who knows me really well will know that this is not going to be easy for me, my love of chocolate is immense, especially at Easter and I would rather stick pins in my eyes than give up chocolate.  However, to raise money for BHF I have decided is worth it and I'm up for the challenge.

I am grateful for any donation, no matter how small.  Thank you for reading x

charity.description: With your support, we aim to fund over £100 million of research each year into all heart and circulatory diseases and the things that cause them. Heart diseases. Stroke. Vascular dementia. Diabetes. They're all connected, and they're all under our microscope. Together we can beat heartbreak forever.
charity.name: British Heart Foundation
story:
The pandemic is the biggest challenge we've faced in our 60 year history. And it's led to us being forced to make the devastating decision to cut our 2020 research budget in half. So the truth is, we've never needed people like you more. 

Virtual fundraising challenges like Dechox are a way to help us keep up the pace of progress. Your willpower will be funnelled into ground-breaking science and support for the people who need us most.

Because despite everything else happening at the moment, heart and circulatory diseases are still the world's biggest killers. For the sake of our mums and dads, brothers and sisters, grandparents and friends - we can't drop the ball now.

charity.name: British Heart Foundation
story: Thanks for visiting my page. I'm raising money for the British Heart Foundation and I'd be so grateful for your support. The BHF has helped halve the number of people dying from heart and circulatory disease in the UK but sadly every day hundreds of people lose their lives. It's only thanks to support from people like us that the BHF can create new treatments and discover new cures. £24 could pay for two hours of research by an early career scientist, but every pound helps so please give what you can to help me hit my target. Thanks!

charity.name: British Heart Foundation
story:
It seems fitting to be supporting the British Heart Foundation as granny goes into hospital this week to have a coronary artery bypass graft and valve repair. 

Without all these advances in medicine theses procedures would not be possible, and for that we are truly thankful. 

The pandemic is the biggest challenge we've faced in our 60 year history. And it's led to us being forced to make the devastating decision to cut our 2020 research budget in half. So the truth is, we've never needed people like you more. Virtual fundraising challenges like Dechox are a way to help us keep up the pace of progress. Your willpower will be funnelled into ground-breaking science and support for the people who need us most.Because despite everything else happening at the moment, heart and circulatory diseases are still the world's biggest killers. For the sake of our mums and dads, brothers and sisters, grandparents and friends - we can't drop the ball now.

charity.description: With your support, we aim to fund over £100 million of research each year into all heart and circulatory diseases and the things that cause them. Heart diseases. Stroke. Vascular dementia. Diabetes. They're all connected, and they're all under our microscope. Together we can beat heartbreak forever.
charity.name: British Heart Foundation
story:
The pandemic is the biggest challenge we've faced in our 60 year history. And it's led to us being forced to make the devastating decision to cut our 2020 research budget in half. So the truth is, we've never needed people like you more. 

Virtual fundraising challenges like Dechox are a way to help us keep up the pace of progress. Your willpower will be funnelled into ground-breaking science and support for the people who need us most.

Because despite everything else happening at the moment, heart and circulatory diseases are still the world's biggest killers. For the sake of our mums and dads, brothers and sisters, grandparents and friends - we can't drop the ball now.

charity.name: British Heart Foundation
story:
Thanks for taking the time to visit my JustGiving page.

Donating through JustGiving is simple, fast and totally secure. Your details are safe with JustGiving - they'll never sell them on or send unwanted emails. Once you donate, they'll send your money directly to the charity. So it's the most efficient way to donate - saving time and cutting costs for the charity.

Gary’s family have created this page so that you can make a donation to the British Heart Foundation rather than sending flowers.

We feel that  this would be a nice way of celebrating Gary’s life, and the friends he made during the many years at work before he retired, and his lifetime of supporting his beloved Leyton Orient

charity.name: British Heart Foundation
story:
Hey 

As many of you may know my baby girl Enya had seizures for many years and we fought to find out the reason 
We was devastated when we were told it was her heart and that it had stopped 9 times in total before having the Amazing pace maker fitted in 2019 at the small age of 9 ! 
This has made things a lot less stressful for us as we know she is safe and I couldn’t thank the doctors enough for making this happen
Because of this I donate monthly to BHF but wanted to do a little more and challenge myself 
I am giving up chocolate for 31 days and trust me it doesn’t sound like a lot to some but it really is to me!
Tayla will be doing this with me 🥰
Pls help us raise some money for an amazing charity !
Without our hearts we are stuffed ❤️

charity.name: British Heart Foundation
story: Thanks for visiting our page. We are raising money for the British Heart Foundation and we'd be so grateful for your support. The BHF has helped halve the number of people dying from heart and circulatory disease in the UK but sadly every day hundreds of people lose their lives. It's only thanks to support from people like us that the BHF can create new treatments and discover new cures. £24 could pay for two hours of research by an early career scientist, but every pound helps so please give what you can to help us hit our target. Thanks!

Virtual fundraising challenges like Dechox are a way to help us keep up the pace of progress. Your willpower will be funnelled into ground-breaking science and support for the people who need us most.

Because despite everything else happening at the moment, heart and circulatory diseases are still the world's biggest killers. For the sake of our mums and dads, brothers and sisters, grandparents and friends - we can't drop the ball now.

I am taking part to help raise money for BHF by going all in and giving up chocolate, sweets and fizzy. Anyone who knows me knows this will be hard, but hopefully you all know I am also stubborn. My stubbornness will get me through because this is a good cause and shows that what we eat and drink has lasting physical and mental effects. 

This is not just to raise money for BHF but give a reason to fight for a better me.

Thank you all for you support

story:
Hey guys!!
So, many people don't know that the British heart foundation sponsor the heart surgery ward at Leeds General infirmary where Stacey has had many surgerys... so I have decided I am going to join my amazing team at work and give up chocolate for March in order to raise money for them!
And anyone who knows me will know how hard that is going to be for me 🤣🤣
So please, even if you can donate a small amount i would appreciate it!! And if you can't donate if you could share my page it would be amazing!!

story: Thanks for visiting my page. I'm raising money for the British Heart Foundation and I'd be so grateful for your support. The BHF has helped halve the number of people dying from heart and circulatory disease in the UK but sadly every day hundreds of people lose their lives. It's only thanks to support from people like us that the BHF can create new treatments and discover new cures. £24 could pay for two hours of research by an early career scientist, but every pound helps so please give what you can to help me hit my target. Thanks!

charity.name: British Heart Foundation
story:
People who know me well, know how much I love my chocolate
so when I came across this British Heart Foundation fundraising event I thought   ‘ I’m going to give it a go, how hard can it
be – 31 days without chocolate !!!!  This will be a good challenge for me and earn some money for a great cause at the same time'.   Well, my fellow chocoholics out there will know that giving up chocolate for a whole month is going to be tough, tough, tough – there will be the withdrawal symptoms to deal with, the cravings that hit at any time of the day or night and the mood swings to contend with (my poor husband) but he has broad shoulders and we will be using plastic crockery for the duration.

On a more serious note, heart disease has blighted many of my family members over the years.  My Dad died of a massive heart attack when I was just 14 and I had uncles and an aunt (his brothers and sister) die in the same manner, so it is in remembrance of them that I am doing this.💓

Please help me raise some much needed funds for the BHF so
they can continue to help and support our loved ones, our friends and others through their research into all kinds of debilitating and deadly heart conditions.  Your donation however big or small will be
gratefully received.

Thank you so much 

💓💓💓💓

story:
So anyone who knows me knows that chocolate other than Jack and wine is life!  So I’m going to give it up for March to raise a few quid for BHF.

I have a slight issue with my heart myself, mild mitral regurgitation, which basically means blood can pump the wrong way back out of my heart and cause my heart to work a bit harder to get it to flow the right way (so technical in my explanation aren’t I!) It’s doesn’t affect my life at the moment and I’m hoping that it won’t further down the line. 

Anyway if you could spare a quid or two it’d be appreciated;

charity.description: With your support, we aim to fund over £100 million of research each year into all heart and circulatory diseases and the things that cause them. Heart diseases. Stroke. Vascular dementia. Diabetes. They're all connected, and they're all under our microscope. Together we can beat heartbreak forever.
charity.name: British Heart Foundation
story:
The pandemic is the biggest challenge we've faced in our 60 year history. And it's led to us being forced to make the devastating decision to cut our 2020 research budget in half. So the truth is, we've never needed people like you more. 

Virtual fundraising challenges like Dechox are a way to help us keep up the pace of progress. Your willpower will be funnelled into ground-breaking science and support for the people who need us most.

Because despite everything else happening at the moment, heart and circulatory diseases are still the world's biggest killers. For the sake of our mums and dads, brothers and sisters, grandparents and friends - we can't drop the ball now.

title: My Dechox Fundraising Page
rememberedPersonSummary.name: Marilyn  Hall
Name: My Dechox Fundraising Page

charity.description: With your support, we aim to fund over £100 million of research each year into all heart and circulatory diseases and the things that cause them. Heart diseases. Stroke. Vascular dementia. Diabetes. They're all connected, and they're all under our microscope. Together we can beat heartbreak forever.
charity.name: British Heart Foundation
story:
The pandemic has affected us all in many different ways. For the British Heart Foundation, the pandemic is the biggest challenge they’ve faced in their 60 year history. It’s led to them to have to make the devastating decision to cut their research budget in half. 

Heart and circulatory diseases cause more than a quarter of all deaths in the UK, that’s more than 160,000 deaths each year – an average of 450 deaths each day or one every three minutes in the UK. 

Through my job and being on placement at university, I have seen first hand how heart and circulatory diseases affect  patients and their families. I am doing this dechox to not only challenge myself but to raise awareness for the British Heart Foundation. 

Heart and circulatory diseases are still the world's biggest killers and I believe awareness of this needs to be raised! 

Any donation would make a great difference!

Thank you for taking the time to have a look at my just giving page, I hope everyone is safe and well ❤️

story:
This is the JustGiving page, set up in memory of Audrey Filer. 

A wonderful lady who reached the grand age of 94 .

We have chosen to fundraise for 2 different charities: The British Heart Foundation & MacMillan Cancer Support.

We kindly ask that instead of buying flowers for Audrey’s funeral, donations are made to Audrey’s chosen charities.

Thank You very much for your support.

Audrey’s Family 

XXX

Thanks for taking the time to visit my JustGiving page.

Donating through JustGiving is simple, fast and totally secure. Your details are safe with JustGiving - they'll never sell them on or send unwanted emails. Once you donate, they'll send your money directly to the charity. So it's the most efficient way to donate - saving time and cutting costs for the charity.

Because despite everything else happening at the moment, heart and circulatory diseases are still the world's biggest killers. For the sake of our mums and dads, brothers and sisters, grandparents and friends - we can't drop the ball now.

charity.name: British Heart Foundation
story: Thanks for visiting my page. I'm raising money for the British Heart Foundation and I'd be so grateful for your support. The BHF has helped halve the number of people dying from heart and circulatory disease in the UK but sadly every day hundreds of people lose their lives. It's only thanks to support from people like us that the BHF can create new treatments and discover new cures. £24 could pay for two hours of research by an early career scientist, but every pound helps so please give what you can to help me hit my target. Thanks!

charity.name: British Heart Foundation
story:
With deep sadness and great shock we all mourn the loss of a wonderful and much loved woman. 

Christine Doughty, a lady who departed with no warning, and leaves a great big gap in so many lives - was taken from us by her ailing heart. 

Unfortunately we are only able to have very limited numbers at the funeral, and can only bring family flowers.

So for those who wish to remember mum with a floral tribute, we’re asking that you please donate to the British Heart Foundation - an organisation that mum raised money for (making and selling her lovely jam), and had direct contact with after her heart surgery. She chose the BFH herself in life.

story:
So as most of you know. I cant go a day with out chocolate.

 So I am going to go a month with out chocolate.  

Not just to raise money for the BHF which means a lot to me as mum passed away 6 ywars ago, but because of this pandemic chocolate has been a life saver.  But things are getting back to "normal" slowly so I will be pushing myself to give it up.

charity.name: British Heart Foundation
story:
Many years ago when Flo was 3 , Flo, Mummy , Daddy, Uncle Bear and Aunty Rach all went to Cornwall to see Aunty Mel . We all ate too much and had lots of wine 🍷 but when the weekend was over everyone got ill (except mummy !!) Flo was so ill, she ended up in hospital with suspected Sepsis and unknown to us all, Uncle Bear (Ad) was really ill and he didn’t know it . A few weeks later after being ill for a while Ad was diagnosed with heart failiure linked to infection . He was pretty poorly .

We are all so grateful that Uncle Bear made it through and he’s still here to bring us books and chocolate  and fix our broken stuff 😜 and text Daddy and keep him sane in a crazy house of women 

Heart failiure doesn’t go away but hopefully  with the right support, Uncle Bear will be able to stay well and keep making us laugh ! .

So this year Flo and I have decided to give up chocolate for March to raise money for the British Heart Foundation, who I know have offered so much support .

Really the sponsorship is for Flo, because  at 7 years old, when chocolate is literally your favourite thing in the world, giving it up will be hard . But she’s very determined,  so any donations will spur her on !! 

I’m just doing it to shrink my bum ! 

Thanks all ! We’ll keep you updated !

Much love ❤️

charity.name: British Heart Foundation
story: Thanks for visiting my page. I'm raising money for the British Heart Foundation and I'd be so grateful for your support. As part of my DofE bronze award, I am doing a half hour  fitness class twice weekly with my family to raise money for this great cause. The BHF has helped halve the number of people dying from heart and circulatory disease in the UK but sadly every day hundreds of people lose their lives. It's only thanks to support from people like us that the BHF can create new treatments and discover new cures. £24 could pay for two hours of research by an early career scientist, but every pound helps so please give what you can to help me hit my target. Thanks!

story:
Alongside my challenge to run 100 miles in 28 days for Refuge I will also take on this challenge. 

I am a binge eater and I binge on sweet sugary snacks so for 1 month I will cut it all out in order to hopefully loose weight as well as keep my heart healthy. 

The pandemic is the biggest challenge we've faced in our 60 year history. And it's led to us being forced to make the devastating decision to cut our 2020 research budget in half. So the truth is, we've never needed people like you more. Virtual fundraising challenges like Dechox are a way to help us keep up the pace of progress. Your willpower will be funnelled into ground-breaking science and support for the people who need us most.Because despite everything else happening at the moment, heart and circulatory diseases are still the world's biggest killers. For the sake of our mums and dads, brothers and sisters, grandparents and friends - we can't drop the ball now.

story: Over 3 years ago in 2017 my younger sister amy was sent into great almond street hospital with a heart murmur. Thankfully with the support of the British heart foundation she was brought home safe just in time for Christmas. Again when she was sent into hospital a year later in 2018. Although this time the British heart foundation has offered support to the whole family and amy is now home safe. So to thank BHF I have decided to participate in Dechox 2021 so other families can have that support.

story:
I absolutely love chocolate! I currently eat at least two chocolate bars/bags every day. I'm addicted to it and I'd really like not to be! I know how bad too much sugar can be, but I just love anything sweet and always have to have a pudding after every meal - yes breakfast pudding is a thing! Giving it up will be so hard, I have so little willpower when it comes to chocolate. When I found this challenge in aid of the British Heart Foundation, I thought it was the perfect opportunity to give it all up for a month, chocolate, cake, sweets, biscuits, the lot! If you could donate the price of a chocolate bar, that would be incredible. So many charities have suffered during the pandemic and anything we can give will help them so much. Thank you x

British Heart Foundation 

The pandemic is the biggest challenge we've faced in our 60 year history. And it's led to us being forced to make the devastating decision to cut our 2020 research budget in half. eventName: 1000 miles for our Name a Puppy campaign
story:
Cameron Optometry is raising funds for the Guide Dogs Scotland Name a Puppy campaign. The staff at the practice regularly sees how blind or partially sighted people rely on guide dogs and we know how much they enrich their lives. So, the whole practice has been raising funds to put a puppy through its first year of training. It costs over £5,000 to support each guide dog puppy. We aren't far off so are hoping this challenge will help us raise the final £1000 we need to hit the £5000 target. 

So, our team challenge is to walk, run or swim at least 1000 miles between us throughout March 2021. Everyone is taking on their own personal challenge, from cold water swimming, to running/walking an impressive 100 miles. We would so appreciate your support to get us over the line. Then we'll be looking for suggestions for names! 

About Guide Dogs Scotland

When someone loses their sight, Guide Dogs Scotland is there to make sure they don’t lose their freedom as well. Their Edinburgh, Forfar and Glasgow teams provide life-changing mobility services to adults, children and young people with sight loss throughout Scotland. It is their mission to not rest until people who are blind or partially sighted can enjoy the same freedom of movement as everyone else. Find more about the great work of the Guide Dogs in Scotland here www.guidedogs.org.uk/guide-dogs-scotland/

Almost two million people in the UK are living with sight loss that has a significant impact on their daily lives. Of those, around 180,000 rarely leave their homes alone and lead lonely, isolated lives. Guide Dogs works for a world where people with sight loss are never left out of life, for a world where being blind or partially sighted is not what defines you. A world with enough support to make the challenges of sight loss no barrier to fulfilling hopes and dreams.

eventName: Great Guide Dogs Virtual Tea Party
story:
Almost two million people in the UK are living with sight loss that has a significant impact on their daily lives. Of those, around 180,000 rarely leave their homes alone and lead lonely, isolated lives. 

Guide Dogs works for a world where people with sight loss are never left out of life, for a world where being blind or partially sighted is not what defines you. A world with enough support to make the challenges of sight loss no barrier to fulfilling hopes and dreams.

story:
Thanks for taking the time to visit my JustGiving page.

Through the course of March I will be walking 62 miles to help Premier Inn raise the money needed for GOSH. 

*********

Together with our team members, guests and suppliers we’re helping to make a difference for the most seriously ill children from across the UK who are being treated at Great Ormond Street Hospital (GOSH).

Every day, 618 children and young people from across the UK arrive at GOSH. Every day, young lives hang in the balance as patients, families and staff battle the most complex illnesses.

Every day, the brightest minds come together to achieve pioneering medical breakthroughs that change the lives of thousands of children. Despite the greatest challenges a child can face, the hospital is a place where being sick does not always mean being sad. And it’s a place where you’ll find – today and every day - some of the bravest people you could ever meet.

https://www.premierinn.com/gb/en/why/gosh-childrens-charity.html

charity.description: Marie Curie provides care and support for people living with any terminal illness across the UK. Our nurses work night and day in people’s homes and our hospices offer specialist care. We also support people emotionally, provide practical information, and match them with trained volunteers.
charity.name: Marie Curie
story:
Every day of your life matters from the first to the last. We believe that everyone living with a terminal illness should be able to get the most from the time they have left, however hard that may sometimes feel. 
We'll be here for you and your family when you may feel like no-one else is, to help you cope when you don't know how. Marie Curie Nurses care for you in your home, when you need them most, day or night. Our hospices are at the heart of communities around the UK. And our trained volunteers and advisers are here for you with practical information and support when you don't know what to do next or just need to talk. 
We'll be by your side with care and support every step of the way, bringing light in the darkest hours.

Our nurses work night and day in people’s homes and our hospices offer specialist care. We also support people emotionally, provide practical information, and match them with trained volunteers.
charity.name: Marie Curie
story:
On the 20/11/2020 an angel was born. Not only my Aunty P, but my best friend. After 6 long months, she lost her fight to brain cancer. 


She was taken care of by the most amazing staff, nurses and doctors in the Marie Curie Hospice where she was comforted as much as she could have been during her final months. The pandemic stopped us, her family, from being able to see her, and stopped us from spending the precious time that we would have had left with her. They took care of her in ways that we weren’t able to and for that, we will forever be grateful. 


To raise awareness for brain cancer and all of the work that the Marie Curie Hospice do, me and my mum will be walking a marathon once every month until July 5th to mark my Auntie P’s birthday. 


Please share as much as possible to raise awareness and there will be a link in my bio where you can donate to the Marie Curie if you’re able to, it would be so appreciated❤️

eventName: Morrisons in store  Fundraising Table with craft packs and tree of light
story:
This March, Morrisons and Marie Curie are working side by side to raise vital funds for frontline nurses to help dying people and their loved ones.

This has been a hard year for everyone. Weve faced challenging times as a nation, and we know it's the small moments that bring people together. Such moments can be made possible for dying people and their loved ones by the expert care of Marie Curie Nurses, who can bring care, comfort and clarity at the very toughest time. 

Your support means the world to people affected by terminal illness.  From picking your daffodil in-store and wearing it with pride, to taking on your own fundraising challenge you're making vital care possible.

Put simply, without the support people like you highly skilled Marie Curie Nurses couldn't continue giving vital care to people living with a terminal illness and their families.

charity.description: Marie Curie provides care and support for people living with any terminal illness across the UK. Our nurses work night and day in people’s homes and our hospices offer specialist care. We also support people emotionally, provide practical information, and match them with trained volunteers.
charity.name: Marie Curie
story:
Every day of your life matters from the first to the last. We believe that everyone living with a terminal illness should be able to get the most from the time they have left, however hard that may sometimes feel. 
We'll be here for you and your family when you may feel like no-one else is, to help you cope when you don't know how. Marie Curie Nurses care for you in your home, when you need them most, day or night. Our hospices are at the heart of communities around the UK. And our trained volunteers and advisers are here for you with practical information and support when you don't know what to do next or just need to talk. 
We'll be by your side with care and support every step of the way, bringing light in the darkest hours.

story:
Thanks for taking the time to visit my JustGiving page.


Ella (in her pushchair 😂) and I will be taking part in Marie Curie's Step into Spring, and will be aiming to walk 10,000 steps a day for each day in March. We would love your support and Tom will be joining us on his days off.

Marie Curie Nurses and hospices have been working tirelessly throughout the pandemic, providing vital care and support, and a listening ear to people in need. They can’t keep doing this without support though.

Tom and I have seen the fantastic care that they provide and would be grateful for any donation, however small to help Marie Curie support other familes.

charity.description: Marie Curie provides care and support for people living with any terminal illness across the UK. Our nurses work night and day in people’s homes and our hospices offer specialist care. We also support people emotionally, provide practical information, and match them with trained volunteers.
charity.name: Marie Curie
story:
Every day of your life matters from the first to the last. We believe that everyone living with a terminal illness should be able to get the most from the time they have left, however hard that may sometimes feel. 
We'll be here for you and your family when you may feel like no-one else is, to help you cope when you don't know how. Marie Curie Nurses care for you in your home, when you need them most, day or night. Our hospices are at the heart of communities around the UK. And our trained volunteers and advisers are here for you with practical information and support when you don't know what to do next or just need to talk. 
We'll be by your side with care and support every step of the way, bringing light in the darkest hours.

Like so many of us unfortunately we know too many people that have suffered because of cancer or still suffering.With covid massively effecting fundraising this year for vital charities I would like to do my bit. I am hoping to raise £390 which will provide hospice care for a patient for one night. Hospices are a sanctuary and a blessing in the most horrific of times for a patient and their family, they give dignity to people in the last chapter of their life. If you could spare any amount I would be extremely grateful. I will post photos of my steps through March and hope we can raise a good amount for Marie curie, 

Much love 

Kirsty

story: Hi everyone! I'm taking part in Marie Curie's Step into Spring 2021 Challenge and will be walking 10,000 steps every day in March to raise money for this amazing charity. charity.name: Marie Curie
story:
For Marie Curie our Great Daffodil Appeal month of March is normally full of some wonderful fundraising & fabulous support and this year we need your help more than ever before. With no collections in supermarkets, daffodil pins in shops & businesses or face to face events, we really do need you to help us reach all corners of our communities, to give everyone the chance to donate and get their virtual daffodil. Our nurses have never been busier as all health care professionals strive to keep patients at home for their care. Please donate to our virtual collection so that we can continue to help care for our patients and support their families through such a difficult & emotional time.

charity.description: Marie Curie provides care and support for people living with any terminal illness across the UK. Our nurses work night and day in people’s homes and our hospices offer specialist care. We also support people emotionally, provide practical information, and match them with trained volunteers.
charity.name: Marie Curie
story:
Riley, Gillian and Anne are walking 300000 steps in March in memory of their beautiful Auntie Nicola, sister and daughter who we lost to a glioblastoma brain tumour in 2017.  Nicola was cared for by the amazing team in the Marie Curie, Edinburgh hospice from May - July 2017.  Our family will be forever grateful to the hospice for their endless care to Nicola and support they gave our whole family at that incredibly difficult time.

Our hospice is a warm and welcoming place, supporting people in Edinburgh and their loved ones with expert care, every day of the year. Our doctors, nurses, physiotherapists and social workers are supported by a team of volunteers, who play a vital role in the running of the hospice.Some of the people we support stay in our in-patient unit, where relatives and friends can visit any time of the day or night and stay with their loved ones if they wish to.We also support local people with clinics, therapies and activities during the day including one-to-one care, groups and things like reiki and massage. As well as people with a terminal illness, we also support carers and families with things like bereavement support groups where people can share their experiences and feelings.Thank you for supporting us, and helping to make sure more people with a terminal illness in Edinburgh get the care and support they need.

story:
Thanks for taking the time to visit my JustGiving page.

At a time when you just don't know where to turn; when you feel so desolate, alone and filled with unbelievable grief, Marie Curie provides calm understanding and truly caring support. I will be forever grateful to Mary who stayed through the night; sensitively caring for us and allowing my wife to pass peacefully and gracefully in my arms at home.

Floral tributes are welcome but funds donated to this valuable service will leave a more lasting impression. 

Thank you for your kindness.

Donald Lawson

We'll be here for you and your family when you may feel like no-one else is, to help you cope when you don't know how. Marie Curie Nurses care for you in your home, when you need them most, day or night. Our hospices are at the heart of communities around the UK. And our trained volunteers and advisers are here for you with practical information and support when you don't know what to do next or just need to talk.
We'll be by your side with care and support every step of the way, bringing light in the darkest hours.

charity.name: Marie Curie
story:
At this unprecedented time, when so many people affected by terminal illness are feeling incredibly isolated and helpless, Marie Curie support is all the more vital.

All my Dad wanted was to be at home surrounded by everyone and everything that meant the world to him.  The amazing care my Dad received on his final night from the Marie Curie nurse allowed him to have his final wish, to die at home.

She was so calm and kind.

By donating you will help a Marie Curie nurses to be there for more people, like Dad, who desperately need their care.

charity.name: Marie Curie
story:
Beach Baby is a modern day drama that follows Ethan & Chloe, a young couple whose relationship is tested when they find out that Ethan has lung cancer and Chloe is pregnant. We follow their journey together as we see them trying to deal with this sudden change in both their lives. 

Beach Baby began back in 2018. I had just found out at the time that my grandfather was diagnosed with cancer. When I went to see my grandfather my cousin was there and she had brought her newborn son to see him. When I saw my grandfather hold him, to me I saw life and death all at once. I wanted to make this film for him and for many families around the world who have had to be in that difficult position. Its themes are around loss and struggle while also about loving and acceptance. 

My biggest inspiration for making this film was Spike Jonze’s 2013 film “Her”. I wanted to try and tell a story at times through visuals, I wanted to show times of happiness and times of sadness showcasing the ups and downs of life. My other inspiration was my loved ones who I have lost from cancer. I wanted to show my grandfather the film however he sadly passed away before the film was completed. 

We shot Beach Baby over 7 days in 2019. I was extremely lucky to have such an incredible cast and crew be a part of this experience. Shane Brohan and Marie Devine gave everything they could for their performances in this film. We also ran an IndieGoGo campaign to raise funds for festivals and bring in a composer. By the end of March this year we successfully reached our £500 goal. 

I really hope people enjoy this film as I have poured my heart and soul into this project for almost 3 years now and couldn’t be more proud of what myself and my crew accomplished. I feel extremely lucky to have worked with such a dedicated cast and crew. I also want to thank everyone that has contributed to this film through IndieGoGo and to my friends and family.

charity.name: Marie Curie
story:
The Squat Sqaud has been formed with volunteers from across our wider team at work. 

Laura Harrison,  Wendy Flinn, Cristian Ioana and Emma Porter need your support to raise money for Marie Curie. 

Marie Curie Nurses work on the front line, night and day, in people’s homes across the UK, providing hands-on care and vital emotional support to those with terminal illness and their families

Our challenge: We will each complete 100 squats per day for 30 days in March, that's a total of 12,000 squats between us all! Feel free to challenge us to some weird and wonderful squat variations along with your donations and look out for the pictures we post throughout the very painful month! 

This past 12 months has been tough for everyone, but the nurses need our donations more than ever. Thank you so much for your support for this fundraising event!

charity.description: RNLI volunteer lifeboat crews provide a 24-hour search and rescue service all around the UK and Ireland, while lifeguards keep a careful watch on the UK’s busiest beaches. RNLI lifesaving and drowning prevention depend on supporter fundraising and the generous donations that you and others give.
charity.name: RNLI - Royal National Lifeboat Institution
story:
RNLI lifeboats in Scotland protect hundreds of communities with a 24-hour search and rescue service. Our volunteer crews rely on the safest, most reliable lifeboats and modern stations to launch from. 
Scotlands unrivalled coasts and waters are valued by local communities and visitors alike, with millions travelling to enjoy them, and work on them each year. But the water remains an unpredictable environment that can catch people out. People will always need our help and we will always be there to answer that call.
Keeping a modern fleet of lifeboats maintained, fuelled and ever ready to go to the rescue from all 46 of the lifeboat stations in Scotland is expensive and we rely entirely on voluntary donations to ensure this service is maintained. It costs an average of £155k to run a lifeboat station in Scotland but with the implications of Covid-19, we havent been able to fundraise as normal to help keep our lifeboats afloat. Can you help?

RNLI lifesaving and drowning prevention depend on supporter fundraising and the generous donations that you and others give.
charity.name: RNLI - Royal National Lifeboat Institution
story:
Thanks for taking the time to visit our JustGiving page.

Donating through JustGiving is simple, fast and totally secure. Your details are safe with JustGiving - they'll never sell them on or send unwanted emails. Once you donate, they'll send your money directly to the charity. So it's the most efficient way to donate - saving time and cutting costs for the charity.

Our father Alan, who passed away recently, was a keen sailor. He usually sailed from Burham-on-Crouch in Essex. He sailed for almost all of his life, and well into his eighties. He took part in many Burnham Weeks, competing well and finishing high up the listings for his class. Sailing was his main hobby and provided a break from his busy working life as a publican.  He had the misfortune to be involved in the now infamous Fastnet race where the value of the RNLI became obvious. As well as dad, they rescued many sailors during the time immediately after the gale struck. It's probably not an exaggeration to say that dad owed his life to the bravery and skill of the RNLI crews that day. 

Thank you for donating.

This is a small way of honouring him and the work that the RNLI do.

Clive, Paul & Martin.

story:
Our RNLI lifeboats in Ireland protect hundreds of communities through our 24-hour search and rescue service. They rely on the safest, most reliable lifeboats and modern stations to launch from. Irelands unrivalled coasts and inland waters are valued by local communities and visitors alike, with millions travelling to enjoy them, and work on them each year. But the water remains an unpredictable environment that can catch people out. People will always need our help and we will always be there to answer that call.

For 110 years, the station at Helvick Head operated an all-weather lifeboat until it closed in 1969. After a gap of 28 years, the station re-opened and today operates a B class Atlantic 85 inshore lifeboat.

charity.name: RNLI - Royal National Lifeboat Institution
story:
The RNLI have been hit hard by Covid-19 with most fundraising events being cancelled in 2020 and through the start of 2021.  However the lifesaving service of the RNLI continues to be called on to save lives at sea with its highly trained volunteer crew members being on
call 24 hours a day, ready to risk their lives in all weathers to help
others.  The cost to launch a lifeboat has remained the same but
fundraising income to cover this cost has fallen dramatically with the onset of Covid-19 and the various lockdowns.

The popular annual Raft Race event which we host every year to raise vital funds for Portrush Lifeboat Station has unfortunately been cancelled.   The Raft Race Committee were very much looking forward to running this popular family event this year, particularly after cancelling the 2020 event due to the Covid 19 pandemic. This was the first Raft Race ever to be cancelled, since its inception in the early 1980s.   A number of factors were considered including how the pandemic is unfolding, the programme for the roll out of the new vaccines and the cautious approach required to relaxation of the lockdown measures.

Hopefully 2022 will see a full summer of relative normality and we can
all get back to the things that we enjoy. Until then we would greatly
appreciate any donation through this page to support our Portrush Lifeboat Station and its vital lifesaving service in the community.  We wish to say a massive THANK YOU to everyone who supports this event and the RNLI each year.

Our RNLI lifeboats in Northern Ireland protect hundreds of communities through our 24-hour search and rescue service. They rely on the safest, most reliable lifeboats and modern stations to launch from. Northern Irelands unrivalled coasts and inland waters are valued by local communities and visitors alike, with millions travelling to enjoy them, and work on them each year. But the water remains an unpredictable environment that can catch people out. People will always need the help of the RNLI and we will always be there to answer that call.

charity.description: Right now, millions of children are in danger. They face violence, disease, hunger and the chaos of war and disaster. Unicef ensures more children get life-saving food, vaccinations, education and protection than anyone else. With your help, we can build a safer world for children. unicef.org.uk
charity.name: Unicef UK
eventName: Running to raise money for Yemen
story:
BBC news at 10 featured a piece about Yemen last night (23/02/2012). Yemen is the largest humanitarian crisis in the world, which given the world at the moment is a pretty big deal. 

The report told the story of a 1-year old boy, who was half the weight he should be, and too weak to hold his head up. He was suffering from severe acute malnutrition. 

According to Unicef, nearly 2.3 million children under the age of five in Yemen are projected to suffer from acute malnutrition in 2021. Of these, 400,000 are expected to suffer from severe acute malnutrition and could die if they do not receive urgent treatment. 

On top of all that, now they have to try and deal with the coronavirus.

No one has had it easy recently, but this story made me realise that despite our complaining about missed opportunities during lockdown, we don't know how good we've got it. Normal people in Yemen have been being bombed and killed almost non-stop for six years, through no fault of their own. 

Most parents there are relying on international aid to feed their families. That's a huge demand, so I'd like to try and raise some money to help. 

I'm going to run 400km over the next few months. One kilometer for every thousand children suffering with severe acute malnutrition. I will post updates to let you know how I'm getting on. 

Unicef's page for the Yemen Crisis:  https://www.unicef.org/emergencies/yemen-crisis#what-unicef-is-doing 

This video explains what is happening: https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=2nzDs2-seD8 

This is a show called 'The Inquiry' about Yemen on BBC Radio 4: https://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/m00045sl

charity.name: Unicef UK
story:
I am fundraising because Unicef urgently need funds to expand the scale and scope of their work supporting children affected by coronavirus, especially in countries with weaker health systems.
Just £30 could provide a full kit to protect a health-worker on the frontline, including gloves, masks and coveralls, while just £43 could help provide 1,680 pairs of disposable gloves for health workers.
The impact of a large-scale outbreak of coronavirus on children, especially poor and vulnerable children, has been immense. Children are at risk from the disease, but also from the disruption to health and education services, impacts on caregivers, and separation from family members.
Unicef has been working closely with governments and the World Health Organization (WHO) since the start of the coronavirus outbreak. Donations made to my page will help to limit the spread of the virus and reduce the impact on children and families.

charity.description: WaterAid is an international not-for-profit, determined to make clean water, decent toilets and good hygiene normal for everyone, everywhere within a generation. Only by tackling these three essentials in ways that last can people change their lives for good.
charity.name: WaterAid
story: I'm walking for water so others don't have to. I'm walking for the millions of women and children who walk distances every day to get the water they need for themselves and their families to survive. I'm walking to raise funds so we can make clean water normal for everyone, everywhere. Clean water is a human right that everyone, everywhere should enjoy. But around the world 1 in 10 people have no choice but to drink dirty water, often from remote sources, risking their health, their safety and their chances in life. With clean water, people have an equal chance to be healthy, educated and financially secure. Communities can thrive.

eventName: Access' Manchester to Madagascar - 5,777 miles for WaterAid!
story:
From Manchester to Madagascar 

From 15th February, well be walking, running, cycling, rowing and swimming to travel the 5,777 miles between Manchester to Madagascar, all in aid of highlighting WaterAid's work in Antenanarivo, Madagascar.

5,777 miles might take us a while to complete, so we are going to compete in two teams and start at each end - one team in Manchester and one team in Madagascar - and the objective is to meet in the middle by Easter, and see who gets there first!

Well be walking, running, cycling, rowing or even swimming (when allowed!) to help contribute individually and virtually to the 5,777 miles we need to complete together. 

The objective is to improve all our wellbeing, get us all out more in the fresh air and away from our computers, and to raise £5,777 for a truly magnificent cause!

charity.description: WaterAid is an international not-for-profit, determined to make clean water, decent toilets and good hygiene normal for everyone, everywhere within a generation. Only by tackling these three essentials in ways that last can people change their lives for good.
charity.name: WaterAid
story: I'm walking for water so others don't have to. I'm walking for the millions of women and children who walk distances every day to get the water they need for themselves and their families to survive. I'm walking to raise funds so we can make clean water normal for everyone, everywhere. Clean water is a human right that everyone, everywhere should enjoy. But around the world 1 in 10 people have no choice but to drink dirty water, often from remote sources, risking their health, their safety and their chances in life. With clean water, people have an equal chance to be healthy, educated and financially secure. Communities can thrive.

charity.name: WaterAid
story:
Greetings! I'm walking for water this March so others don't have to. I'm walking for the millions of women and children who walk distances every day to get the water they need for themselves and their families to survive. I'm walking 4km each day throughout March to raise funds so we can make clean water normal for everyone, everywhere. 


I'm doing this at the ripe old age of 81, in collaboration and with the support of other members and friends of the Rotary Club of Portobello, Edinburgh. I will of course provide regular updates. I hope to exceed the distance over the course of the month and your support is very much welcome and indeed appreciated. 


Clean water is a human right that everyone, everywhere should enjoy. But around the world 1 in 10 people have no choice but to drink dirty water, often from remote sources, risking their health, their safety and their chances in life. With clean water, people have an equal chance to be healthy, educated and financially secure. 


If I can manage how to work out how to open my wallet after many years of not having done so, I might just sponsor myself too.


With kind regards, thanks in advance, and please wish me luck! 


Bill

charity.description: WaterAid is an international not-for-profit, determined to make clean water, decent toilets and good hygiene normal for everyone, everywhere within a generation. Only by tackling these three essentials in ways that last can people change their lives for good.
charity.name: WaterAid
story:
Thanks for taking the time to visit our JustGiving page.

We are taking part in a Charity 10,000ft Sky Dive to support an amazing charity, Water Aid on the 16th August 2021 with The Sky Diving Centre in Salisbury.

Water Aid provides clean water, decent toilets and hygiene knowledge to people who don't have access to them. Access to clean water and toilets is a human right and should be a part of daily life for everyone.

Water Aid work with communities to build low-cost, sustainable solutions that meet their needs. They also work with local and national government in the countries they operate, developing solutions to help provide water and toilets for everyone.

We would like to reach a minimum of £1000, any donations would be welcome.
